  number           = {3},
  pages            = {1849--1866},
  url              = {https://doi.org/10.1007/s11071-022-07298-6},
  volume           = {108},
  abstract         = {Gamma oscillations (30-90 Hz) in the brain are known to have an evident relationship with many cognitive processes. Computational models are promising tools for understanding the fundamental mechanisms of oscillatory dynamics and related functions. Early modeling works have devoted to understanding PING (Pyramidal Interneuron Network Gamma) and ING (Interneuron Network Gamma) rhythms, which have been supported by substantial experimental evidence. Despite these achievements, a number of works continue to investigate gamma rhythms focusing on various issues such as the role of resonators in network dynamics, mechanisms for the cross-frequency coupling phenomenon, and data-driven modeling approaches. However, computational models can be developed in various ways, thus making model development a process of great flexibility. Typically, models used for the study of neural oscillations involve spiking network oscillators and neural mass oscillators, while the former can further be classified as biologically realistic and simplified dynamic types according to distinct model developing principles. In this work, we provide a review of recent computational models for gamma oscillations according to different modeling strategies for the study of the above mentioned issues. We conclude that while both spiking neuronal networks and neural mass models are powerful in providing mechanistic insights, the simplicity of neural mass oscillators makes them amenable to dynamic analysis tools and data-fitting approaches, for which reason they may be more productive in relevant studies. Moreover, with rapid developments in neural measuring techniques at multiple scales, it is expected that the theory and methods of computational models across all scales will progress to deepen our understanding of gamma oscillations.},
  creationdate     = {2025-03-02T14:18:08},
  file             = {:Liu2022a.pdf:PDF},
  groups           = {Working regime, PhD},
  modificationdate = {2025-10-02T18:16:12},
  refid            = {Liu2022},
}

