  doi              = {10.1523/ENEURO.0153-16.2017},
  number           = {2},
  pages            = {ENEURO.0153-16.2017},
  url              = {http://www.eneuro.org/content/4/2/ENEURO.0153-16.2017.abstract},
  volume           = {4},
  abstract         = {Unraveling how brain regions communicate is crucial for understanding how the brain processes external and internal information. Neuronal oscillations within and across brain regions have been proposed to play a crucial role in this process. Two main hypotheses have been suggested for routing of information based on oscillations, namely communication through coherence and gating by inhibition. Here, we propose a framework unifying these two hypotheses that is based on recent empirical findings. We discuss a theory in which communication between two regions is established by phase synchronization of oscillations at lower frequencies (&amp;lt;25 Hz), which serve as temporal reference frame for information carried by high-frequency activity (&amp;gt;40 Hz). Our framework, consistent with numerous recent empirical findings, posits that cross-frequency interactions are essential for understanding how large-scale cognitive and perceptual networks operate.},
